In Disney-Pixar’s short “Bao,” an aging Chinese mom suffering from empty-nest syndrome welcomes another chance at motherhood when one of her dumplings springs to life as a lively, giggly dumpling boy. Her newfound happiness is short-lived however, as she soon realizes that nothing stays cute and small forever, and even dumplings grow up. Directed by Domee Shi, who is the first woman to direct a short at Pixar, “Bao” is up for an Oscar this month. (Photo ©2018 Disney-Pixar. All Rights Reserved.)

Caption: Huntington Beach is now battling three lawsuits regarding affordable housing. Over the past two weeks, City attorney Michael Gates has filed two lawsuits against California. After California sued Huntington Beach over affordable housing, new Assemblywoman Cottie Petrie-Norris, a Democrat representing the city, issued a statement decrying the lawsuit. She joined a bipartisan group of state assembly members who signed a letter urging both parties to settle their differences out of court. (Photo courtesy of Cottie Petrie_Norris)

Michael Gates is sworn in as Huntington Beach city attorney in 2015. Over the past two weeks, Gates has filed two lawsuits against California regarding affordable housing. Meanwhile, the state sued Huntington Beach over the same issue, for a total of three lawsuits. A bipartisan group of state assembly members representing Huntington Beach signed a letter urging both parties to settle their differences out of court. DANIEL LANGHORE, Orange County Register

New Assemblyman Tyler Diep, a Republican representing Huntington Beach, said he supports the city’s two lawsuits against California regarding affordable housing “as a legal tactic.” Even so, he joined a bipartisan group of state assembly members who signed a letter urging both parties to settle their differences out of court. Caption: The Fearsome Foursome was the nickname given the defensive line of the Los Angeles Rams in the 1960s to early 1970s. All four of them also acted in TV or film parts to different degrees. Seen here, left to right, are Lamar Lundy, Merlin Olsen, Rosey Grier and Deacon Jones. (File photo)

Elroy Hirsch of the Los Angeles Rams football team demonstrates the style that earned him the nickname Crazylegs, which also served as the title of the bio-pic in which he played himself. He’s seen here in December 1953. (AP Photo/Harold Filan)

UCLA star Kenny Washington eventually broke the color barrier and became the first black player in the NFL when the Los Angeles Rams signed him as they moved to Los Angeles from Cleveland in 1946. He also acted from time to time. He’s seen here, center, with actors Sonny Tufts, left, and Victor Mature, right, in the 1949 film “Easy Living” which starred Mature as a quarterback who learns that he has a heart condition that might kill him if he continues to play. Washington and many other members of the new-in-town Rams played parts as football players. (AP Photo)

Actress Jane Russell, 21, and Bob Waterfield, 22, are shown here on April 26, 1943 at Waterfield’s mother’s home in Van Nuys, after their marriage a few days earlier in Las Vegas. Waterfield was about to enter the Army. He’d be drafted by the Cleveland Rams in 1944, play his first season with the team in that city in 1945, and in 1946 move with the team to Los Angeles where he’d do a little acting and form a production company with Russell in time. (AP Photo)

Actor Kirk Douglas, left, in the title role of “Spartacus” where he played a Roman slave, battles Woody Strode, the former Los Angeles Ram, who earned a Golden Globe nomination for best supporting actor in the film. The scene was filmed in Hollywood in April 1959. (AP Photo)

Actor John Wayne, third from right, poses with members of the Los Angeles Rams defensive line known as the Fearsome Foursome on Nov. 27, 1967. Deacon Jones and Lamar Lundy are at left. Rosey Grier and Merlin Olsen are at right. (AP Photo/David F. Smith)

Los Angeles Rams’ lineman Rosey Grier, seen here during team photos taken in Orange on July 28, 1965, later established himself as an actor with roles in TV shows and movies such as “The Thing With Two Heads.” (AP Photo)

Director and actor Fred Dryer, left, looks from behind the camera at the desert landscape during the filming of “Highway 395” in June  1999 in Lone Pine, Calif. Dryer played football for many years with the Los Angeles Rams before moving into acting. His TV cop show “Hunter” ran for seven seasons. (AP Photo/ Victoria Arocho)
Los Angeles Rams’ David “Deacon” Jones also acted at times in TV shows and movies. (AP Photo/File)

Roosevelt “Rosey” Grier, right, with actress Shirley MacLaine at the Democratic National Convention in August 1969. Grier was a famed defensive lineman for the Los Angeles Rams who later moved into acting for TV and movies. (AP Photo)

Caption: Gucci’s Heron print wallpaper is goals. Gucci, South Coast Plaza :: gucci.com (Photography by Gucci)

Designer Brett Beldock’s soft pink poly velvet slipper chair exudes luxe minimalism. Perched above an exaggerated brass finished base, it creates the perfect perch. $549. CB2 at South Coast Plaza :: cb2.com (Photography courtesy of CB2)

Take your home’s light-heartedness up a notch with Serena & Lily’s felted wool wall pig. It’s well-crafted enough to play nicely in a living space, or try it in a nursery for some easy childhood whimsy. $168 Serena & Lily, Newport Beach :: serenaandlily.com (Photography courtesy of Serena & Lily)

Struggling to eat all your greens? These salad plates by Versace might help. The Scala del Palazzo 21 cm plate in rosa takes inspiration from the marble staircase leading to the private quarters in Versace’s Milanese palazzo in Via Gesù, and features images of the powerful feminine Medusa. $105 each. Versace, South Coast Plaza :: versace.com (Photography by Versace)

Award-winning designer Bethan Gray drew on her own unique heritage – the nomadic Rajasthani clan from India and her upbringing in Wales – to create the Feather Collection for Anthropologie. Anthropologie, South Coast Plaza :: anthropologie.com (Photography by Anthropologie)
